{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KqhSQmhDqJqacQNHh95wwp","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Claude Code subprocess wrapper for AgentTask execution.\n2\t\n3\tThe runner doesn't invoke Claude Code directly — it goes through this\n4\tmodule, which builds the subprocess command, pipes the composed prompt\n5\tover stdin, captures stdout/stderr, and parses the output for the\n6\tsentinel lines that signal success or failure.\n7\t\n8\tDesign choices:\n9\t\n10\t- **Subprocess, not SDK**: we shell out to the ``claude`` CLI (via\n11\t  ``pnpm dlx @anthropic-ai/claude-code``) rather than importing the\n12\t  Anthropic SDK directly. This keeps the harness agnostic to the\n13\t  SDK's runtime requirements and lets us target the same CLI that\n14\t  humans use interactively, which means prompts tested in chat mostly\n15\t  translate cleanly.\n16\t- **Sentinel-based success**: the agent is contracted to emit\n17\t  ``PRD_EXECUTE_OK: <id>`` or ``PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED: <reason>`` as its\n18\t  final line. We parse stdout for these rather than relying on exit\n19\t  codes, because the CLI's exit code semantics are coarse and don't\n20\t  distinguish \"tool refused to run\" from \"tool ran but the task\n21\t  failed\".\n22\t- **Timeout-bounded**: each invocation has a wall-clock timeout\n23\t  (default 10 minutes). Without this, a stuck agent would hang the\n24\t  whole harness indefinitely.\n25\t- **Capability-to-model mapping**: PRDs declare a ``capability`` field\n26\t  (trivial/simple/moderate/complex) that maps to a model. Trivial work\n27\t  goes to haiku, complex to opus, everything in between to sonnet.\n28\t  Individual AgentTasks can override this explicitly via ``task.model``.\n29\t\"\"\"\n30\t\n31\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n32\t\n33\timport json\n34\timport logging\n35\timport re\n36\timport subprocess\n37\timport threading\n38\timport time\n39\tfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n40\tfrom io import StringIO\n41\tfrom pathlib import Path\n42\tfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any\n43\t\n44\tif TYPE_CHECKING:\n45\t    from .style import Element, Styler\n46\t\n47\t\n48\t# ---------- capability -> model mapping ----------\n49\t\n50\t\n51\tCAPABILITY_MODELS: dict[str, str] = {\n52\t    \"trivial\": \"haiku\",\n53\t    \"simple\": \"sonnet\",\n54\t    \"moderate\": \"sonnet\",\n55\t    \"complex\": \"opus\",\n56\t}\n57\t\"\"\"PRD capability tier -> Claude model alias.\n58\t\n59\tThe runner picks the model for an AgentTask via (in order):\n60\t\n61\t1. Explicit ``task.model`` if set on the AgentTask\n62\t2. ``capability_to_model(prd.capability)`` if ``task.model_from_capability=True``\n63\t3. Fallback to ``\"sonnet\"`` if nothing else applies\n64\t\n65\tOverridable from the CLI via ``--model`` on ``prd run``.\n66\t\"\"\"\n67\t\n68\t\n69\tdef capability_to_model(capability: str) -> str:\n70\t    \"\"\"Return the default model for a PRD capability tier.\n71\t\n72\t    Unknown capabilities fall back to ``sonnet`` rather than raising —\n73\t    a PRD with an unrecognized capability should still be runnable,\n74\t    just at the default tier.\n75\t    \"\"\"\n76\t    return CAPABILITY_MODELS.get(capability, \"sonnet\")\n77\t\n78\t\n79\t# ---------- result type ----------\n80\t\n81\t\n82\t@dataclass\n83\tclass InvokeResult:\n84\t    \"\"\"Structured outcome of a Claude Code subprocess invocation.\n85\t\n86\t    The runner uses ``success`` to decide whether to continue the\n87\t    workflow (True) or mark the PRD blocked (False). ``failure_reason``\n88\t    is populated on the failure path so error surfaces can be\n89\t    descriptive without having to re-parse the output.\n90\t    \"\"\"\n91\t\n92\t    stdout: str\n93\t    stderr: str\n94\t    exit_code: int\n95\t    success: bool\n96\t    failure_reason: str | None = None\n97\t    tool_counts: dict[str, int] = field(default_factory=dict)\n98\t    sentinel: str | None = None\n99\t\n100\t\n101\t# ---------- sentinel parsing ----------\n102\t\n103\t\n104\t# Anchorless: agents sometimes wrap the sentinel in markdown formatting\n105\t# (backticks, blockquote markers, list bullets) when ``claude --print``\n106\t# renders their final line. Substring-style matching is more forgiving\n107\t# than line-anchored matching and still unambiguous because the marker\n108\t# is a fixed token unlikely to appear naturally in PRD work.\n109\t_SENTINEL_SUCCESS_RE = re.compile(r\"PRD_EXECUTE_OK:\\s*(\\S[^\\n`]*)\")\n110\t_SENTINEL_FAILURE_RE = re.compile(r\"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED:\\s*(\\S[^\\n`]*)\")\n111\t\n112\t\n113\tdef _parse_sentinels(\n114\t    stdout: str,\n115\t    success_marker: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\",\n116\t    failure_marker: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\",\n117\t) -> tuple[bool, str | None]:\n118\t    \"\"\"Scan ``stdout`` for sentinel lines and return (success, failure_reason).\n119\t\n120\t    The regex targets the default marker shape. Non-default markers\n121\t    passed by the runner (e.g. from an AgentTask that customized them)\n122\t    fall through to literal substring matching.\n123\t\n124\t    Precedence: failure beats success. If both sentinels appear in the\n125\t    output, we treat it as failure — the agent shouldn't emit both and\n126\t    the conservative interpretation is \"something went wrong mid-task\".\n127\t    \"\"\"\n128\t    # Custom marker fast path: if the caller specified non-default markers,\n129\t    # fall back to substring matching since we can't know their regex shape.\n130\t    if success_marker != \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\" or failure_marker != \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\":\n131\t        failure_hit = f\"{failure_marker}:\" in stdout\n132\t        success_hit = f\"{success_marker}:\" in stdout\n133\t        if failure_hit:\n134\t            # Best-effort reason extraction: everything after the marker on its line\n135\t            for line in stdout.splitlines():\n136\t                if line.startswith(f\"{failure_marker}:\"):\n137\t                    reason = line.split(\":\", 1)[1].strip()\n138\t                    return False, reason or \"unspecified failure\"\n139\t            return False, \"unspecified failure\"\n140\t        if success_hit:\n141\t            return True, None\n142\t        return (\n143\t            False,\n144\t            f\"agent output contained no {success_marker} or {failure_marker} sentinel\",\n145\t        )\n146\t\n147\t    # Default marker path: use precompiled regexes.\n148\t    failure_match = _SENTINEL_FAILURE_RE.search(stdout)\n149\t    if failure_match:\n150\t        return False, failure_match.group(1).strip()\n151\t\n152\t    success_match = _SENTINEL_SUCCESS_RE.search(stdout)\n153\t    if success_match:\n154\t        return True, None\n155\t\n156\t    return (\n157\t        False,\n158\t        \"agent output contained no PRD_EXECUTE_OK or PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED sentinel\",\n159\t    )\n160\t\n161\t\n162\t# ---------- stream-json event summarization ----------\n163\t\n164\t\n165\tdef _summarize_stream_event(\n166\t    event: dict[str, Any],\n167\t) -> tuple[\"Element | None\", str, str]:\n168\t    \"\"\"Turn one Claude Code stream-json event into (element, display_text, agent_text).\n169\t\n170\t    Returns:\n171\t        element: the semantic :class:`~darkfactory.style.Element` for this\n172\t            event, or ``None`` to skip display entirely.\n173\t        display_text: a one-line human-readable summary. Empty string when\n174\t            ``element`` is ``None``.\n175\t        agent_text: the substring that should be appended to the agent-text\n176\t            buffer used for sentinel matching. Empty string for non-text\n177\t            events. Sentinels can only appear in assistant text, so we\n178\t            accumulate text aggressively and let the parser scan it.\n179\t\n180\t    The Claude Code stream-json envelope shapes we care about:\n181\t\n182\t    - ``{\"type\": \"system\", \"subtype\": \"init\", ...}`` — start of session\n183\t    - ``{\"type\": \"assistant\", \"message\": {\"content\": [...]}}`` — model output\n184\t        block (text or tool_use)\n185\t    - ``{\"type\": \"user\", \"message\": {\"content\": [{\"type\": \"tool_result\", ...}]}}``\n186\t        — tool result echoed back from the harness's perspective\n187\t    - ``{\"type\": \"stream_event\", \"event\": {\"type\": \"content_block_delta\",\n188\t        \"delta\": {\"type\": \"text_delta\", \"text\": \"...\"}}}`` — partial message\n189\t        chunks (only when --include-partial-messages is set)\n190\t    - ``{\"type\": \"result\", \"subtype\": \"success\"|\"error_max_turns\"|..., ...}``\n191\t        — terminal event with the final message and stats\n192\t\n193\t    Anything not in this list is skipped (element=None).\n194\t    \"\"\"\n195\t    from .style import Element\n196\t\n197\t    etype = event.get(\"type\")\n198\t\n199\t    if etype == \"system\":\n200\t        subtype = event.get(\"subtype\", \"?\")\n201\t        return (Element.SYSTEM, f\"[system] {subtype}\", \"\")\n202\t\n203\t    if etype == \"assistant\":\n204\t        msg = event.get(\"message\", {}) or {}\n205\t        content = msg.get(\"content\", []) or []\n206\t        # Pick the most informative block. A single assistant event can\n207\t        # contain multiple content blocks; we summarize each on its own line\n208\t        # by returning only the first here and recursing for the others\n209\t        # would over-complicate the contract — instead we join them with\n210\t        # ' | '.\n211\t        bits: list[str] = []\n212\t        text_accum: list[str] = []\n213\t        has_tool_use = False\n214\t        only_thinking = True\n215\t        for block in content:\n216\t            btype = block.get(\"type\")\n217\t            if btype == \"text\":\n218\t                only_thinking = False\n219\t                text = block.get(\"text\") or \"\"\n220\t                text_accum.append(text)\n221\t                # Show first 200 chars on a single line; the buffer keeps\n222\t                # the full text for sentinel parsing.\n223\t                snippet = text.replace(\"\\n\", \" \").strip()\n224\t                if len(snippet) > 200:\n225\t                    snippet = snippet[:197] + \"...\"\n226\t                if snippet:\n227\t                    bits.append(f\"text: {snippet}\")\n228\t            elif btype == \"tool_use\":\n229\t                only_thinking = False\n230\t                has_tool_use = True\n231\t                name = block.get(\"name\", \"?\")\n232\t                inp = block.get(\"input\", {}) or {}\n233\t                # Render a few high-signal inputs concisely.\n234\t                hint = \"\"\n235\t                if isinstance(inp, dict):\n236\t                    if \"command\" in inp:\n237\t                        hint = f\" {str(inp['command'])[:120]}\"\n238\t                    elif \"file_path\" in inp:\n239\t                        hint = f\" {inp['file_path']}\"\n240\t                    elif \"pattern\" in inp:\n241\t                        hint = f\" /{inp['pattern'][:60]}/\"\n242\t                    elif \"path\" in inp:\n243\t                        hint = f\" {inp['path']}\"\n244\t                bits.append(f\"tool_use: {name}{hint}\")\n245\t            elif btype == \"thinking\":\n246\t                # Don't echo full thinking — too noisy. Just note it happened.\n247\t                bits.append(\"thinking\")\n248\t            else:\n249\t                only_thinking = False\n250\t                bits.append(f\"{btype}\")\n251\t\n252\t        if not bits:\n253\t            return (None, \"\", \"\\n\".join(text_accum))\n254\t\n255\t        display = \" | \".join(bits)\n256\t        if has_tool_use:\n257\t            element: Element = Element.TOOL_CALL\n258\t        elif only_thinking and bits == [\"thinking\"]:\n259\t            element = Element.THINKING\n260\t        else:\n261\t            element = Element.ASSISTANT_TEXT\n262\t        return (element, display, \"\\n\".join(text_accum))\n263\t\n264\t    if etype == \"user\":\n265\t        msg = event.get(\"message\", {}) or {}\n266\t        content = msg.get(\"content\", []) or []\n267\t        for block in content:\n268\t            if block.get(\"type\") == \"tool_result\":\n269\t                raw = block.get(\"content\")\n270\t                # tool_result content can be a string or a list of blocks\n271\t                if isinstance(raw, list):\n272\t                    raw = \" \".join(\n273\t                        b.get(\"text\", \"\") for b in raw if isinstance(b, dict)\n274\t                    )\n275\t                snippet = (raw or \"\").replace(\"\\n\", \" \").strip()\n276\t                if len(snippet) > 200:\n277\t                    snippet = snippet[:197] + \"...\"\n278\t                is_error = block.get(\"is_error\")\n279\t                err = \" (error)\" if is_error else \"\"\n280\t                elem = Element.ERROR if is_error else Element.TOOL_RESULT\n281\t                return (elem, f\"tool_result{err}: {snippet}\", \"\")\n282\t        return (None, \"\", \"\")\n283\t\n284\t    if etype == \"stream_event\":\n285\t        ev = event.get(\"event\", {}) or {}\n286\t        if ev.get(\"type\") == \"content_block_delta\":\n287\t            delta = ev.get(\"delta\", {}) or {}\n288\t            if delta.get(\"type\") == \"text_delta\":\n289\t                text = delta.get(\"text\") or \"\"\n290\t                # Don't log every micro-delta — too noisy. But DO accumulate\n291\t                # text into the agent buffer so sentinels build up.\n292\t                return (None, \"\", text)\n293\t        return (None, \"\", \"\")\n294\t\n295\t    if etype == \"rate_limit_event\":\n296\t        info = event.get(\"rate_limit_info\", {}) or {}\n297\t        status = info.get(\"status\", \"?\")\n298\t        util = info.get(\"utilization\")\n299\t        rl_type = info.get(\"rateLimitType\", \"?\")\n300\t        util_str = f\" {util:.0%}\" if isinstance(util, (int, float)) else \"\"\n301\t        return (Element.RATE_LIMIT, f\"[rate_limit] {rl_type} {status}{util_str}\", \"\")\n302\t\n303\t    if etype == \"result\":\n304\t        subtype = event.get(\"subtype\", \"?\")\n305\t        msg = event.get(\"result\") or \"\"\n306\t        snippet = str(msg).replace(\"\\n\", \" \").strip()\n307\t        if len(snippet) > 200:\n308\t            snippet = snippet[:197] + \"...\"\n309\t        # Extract token usage if present — render result events bold so the\n310\t        # token count stands out (AC-3).\n311\t        usage = event.get(\"usage\", {}) or {}\n312\t        input_tokens = usage.get(\"input_tokens\", 0) or 0\n313\t        output_tokens = usage.get(\"output_tokens\", 0) or 0\n314\t        total_tokens = input_tokens + output_tokens\n315\t        token_str = f\" [{total_tokens:,} tokens]\" if total_tokens else \"\"\n316\t        display = f\"[result] {subtype}{token_str} {snippet}\".strip()\n317\t        # Use TOKEN_COUNT element when usage info is present so the line\n318\t        # renders bold; fall back to SYSTEM otherwise.\n319\t        result_elem = Element.TOKEN_COUNT if total_tokens else Element.SYSTEM\n320\t        # The result.result field contains the final text, which is where\n321\t        # the sentinel typically lands.\n322\t        return (result_elem, display, str(msg))\n323\t\n324\t    # Unknown event type — log nothing, accumulate nothing.\n325\t    return (None, \"\", \"\")\n326\t\n327\t\n328\t# ---------- main entry point ----------\n329\t\n330\t\n331\tdef invoke_claude(\n332\t    prompt: str,\n333\t    tools: list[str],\n334\t    model: str,\n335\t    cwd: Path,\n336\t    *,\n337\t    sentinel_success: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\",\n338\t    sentinel_failure: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\",\n339\t    timeout_seconds: int = 600,\n340\t    executable: str = \"pnpm\",\n341\t    dry_run: bool = False,\n342\t    logger: logging.Logger | None = None,\n343\t    styler: \"Styler | None\" = None,\n344\t    _argv_override: list[str] | None = None,\n345\t) -> InvokeResult:\n346\t    \"\"\"Run Claude Code as a subprocess with the given prompt and return the result.\n347\t\n348\t    The command built is::\n349\t\n350\t        pnpm dlx @anthropic-ai/claude-code --print \\\\\n351\t            --model <model> \\\\\n352\t            --allowed-tools \"<comma-joined tools>\"\n353\t\n354\t    ``prompt`` is piped to the subprocess via stdin. ``cwd`` sets the\n355\t    working directory so relative paths the agent reads/writes resolve\n356\t    correctly.\n357\t\n358\t    Agent stdout is streamed line-by-line to ``logger`` in real time so\n359\t    the user can see progress. The full stdout is also captured in a\n360\t    buffer so sentinel parsing at the end works as before.\n361\t\n362\t    On timeout, returns a failure result with the reason populated and\n363\t    any partial stdout captured before the kill — does NOT raise. This\n364\t    matches the runner's expectation that invoke returns a structured\n365\t    result no matter what.\n366\t\n367\t    ``dry_run=True`` skips the actual subprocess entirely and returns a\n368\t    synthetic success result with empty output. This is what ``prd\n369\t    plan`` uses to show what WOULD happen without spending tokens.\n370\t\n371\t    ``_argv_override`` replaces the ``[\"dlx\", \"@anthropic-ai/claude-code\",\n372\t    ...]`` portion of the command with the given list. Intended for\n373\t    testing with fake subprocesses (e.g. ``executable=\"python\",\n374\t    _argv_override=[\"-c\", \"print('hi')\"]``).\n375\t    \"\"\"\n376\t    if dry_run:\n377\t        return InvokeResult(\n378\t            stdout=f\"[dry-run] would invoke claude with model={model}, \"\n379\t            f\"{len(tools)} tools, prompt={len(prompt)} chars\",\n380\t            stderr=\"\",\n381\t            exit_code=0,\n382\t            success=True,\n383\t            failure_reason=None,\n384\t        )\n385\t\n386\t    log = logger or logging.getLogger(\"darkfactory.invoke\")\n387\t\n388\t    if _argv_override is not None:\n389\t        cmd: list[str] = [executable] + list(_argv_override)\n390\t    else:\n391\t        # --output-format stream-json + --verbose emits JSONL events as\n392\t        # they happen (one event per assistant turn, plus tool results,\n393\t        # rate-limit warnings, and a final result event) instead of\n394\t        # buffering until the process exits. This is what actually makes\n395\t        # streaming-to-logger useful — the raw --print mode writes one\n396\t        # blob at the very end.\n397\t        #\n398\t        # We deliberately do NOT pass --include-partial-messages: per-turn\n399\t        # granularity is plenty for \"is the agent making progress\"\n400\t        # visibility, and per-delta events add a lot of noise without\n401\t        # much extra signal.\n402\t        cmd = [\n403\t            executable,\n404\t            \"dlx\",\n405\t            \"@anthropic-ai/claude-code\",\n406\t            \"--print\",\n407\t            \"--verbose\",\n408\t            \"--output-format\",\n409\t            \"stream-json\",\n410\t            \"--model\",\n411\t            model,\n412\t            \"--allowed-tools\",\n413\t            \",\".join(tools),\n414\t        ]\n415\t\n416\t    try:\n417\t        proc = subprocess.Popen(\n418\t            cmd,\n419\t            stdin=subprocess.PIPE,\n420\t            stdout=subprocess.PIPE,\n421\t            stderr=subprocess.PIPE,\n422\t            cwd=str(cwd),\n423\t            text=True,\n424\t            bufsize=1,  # line-buffered\n425\t        )\n426\t    except FileNotFoundError:\n427\t        return InvokeResult(\n428\t            stdout=\"\",\n429\t            stderr=\"\",\n430\t            exit_code=-1,\n431\t            success=False,\n432\t            failure_reason=f\"executable not found: {executable!r}\",\n433\t        )\n434\t\n435\t    # Send the prompt and close stdin so the CLI knows we're done.\n436\t    assert proc.stdin is not None\n437\t    proc.stdin.write(prompt)\n438\t    proc.stdin.close()\n439\t\n440\t    stdout_buf = StringIO()  # raw stdout (JSONL events when stream-json)\n441\t    agent_text_buf = StringIO()  # accumulated assistant text for sentinel matching\n442\t    stderr_buf = StringIO()\n443\t    tool_counts: dict[str, int] = {}\n444\t    deadline = time.monotonic() + timeout_seconds\n445\t    process_done = threading.Event()\n446\t    timed_out = threading.Event()\n447\t\n448\t    # Drain stderr in a background thread so it doesn't deadlock\n449\t    # the pipe if Claude writes a lot of warnings.\n450\t    def _drain_stderr() -> None:\n451\t        assert proc.stderr is not None\n452\t        for line in proc.stderr:\n453\t            stderr_buf.write(line)\n454\t\n455\t    # Watchdog thread kills the process if it exceeds the deadline.\n456\t    # Uses process_done to wake early when the process finishes normally,\n457\t    # keeping mock-based tests fast.\n458\t    def _watchdog() -> None:\n459\t        remaining = deadline - time.monotonic()\n460\t        if remaining > 0:\n461\t            process_done.wait(timeout=remaining)\n462\t        if not process_done.is_set() and proc.poll() is None:\n463\t            proc.kill()\n464\t            timed_out.set()\n465\t\n466\t    stderr_thread = threading.Thread(target=_drain_stderr, daemon=True)\n467\t    watchdog_thread = threading.Thread(target=_watchdog, daemon=True)\n468\t    stderr_thread.start()\n469\t    watchdog_thread.start()\n470\t\n471\t    # Read stdout line-by-line on the main thread. With stream-json each\n472\t    # line is a JSON envelope; we summarize each event into a one-line log\n473\t    # message and accumulate any assistant text into the sentinel buffer.\n474\t    # Lines that fail to parse as JSON (e.g. tests using a plain stub\n475\t    # subprocess, or unexpected output) fall back to the legacy behavior\n476\t    # of logging the raw line as-is and treating it as agent text.\n477\t    assert proc.stdout is not None\n478\t    try:\n479\t        for line in proc.stdout:\n480\t            stdout_buf.write(line)\n481\t            stripped = line.rstrip(\"\\n\")\n482\t            if not stripped:\n483\t                continue\n484\t            try:\n485\t                event = json.loads(stripped)\n486\t            except json.JSONDecodeError:\n487\t                # Not JSON — preserve old behavior. Useful for tests that\n488\t                # stub the subprocess with plain text and for diagnostics.\n489\t                if styler is not None:\n490\t                    from .style import Element\n491\t                    import sys\n492\t\n493\t                    print(\n494\t                        styler.render(Element.ASSISTANT_TEXT, stripped),\n495\t                        file=sys.stderr,\n496\t                    )\n497\t                else:\n498\t                    log.info(\"agent: %s\", stripped)\n499\t                agent_text_buf.write(stripped + \"\\n\")\n500\t                continue\n501\t\n502\t            if not isinstance(event, dict):\n503\t                log.info(\"agent: %s\", stripped)\n504\t                continue\n505\t\n506\t            element, display_text, agent_text = _summarize_stream_event(event)\n507\t            # Accumulate tool-call counts from assistant events.\n508\t            if event.get(\"type\") == \"assistant\":\n509\t                for block in (event.get(\"message\") or {}).get(\"content\") or []:\n510\t                    if block.get(\"type\") == \"tool_use\":\n511\t                        name = block.get(\"name\") or \"unknown\"\n512\t                        tool_counts[name] = tool_counts.get(name, 0) + 1\n513\t            if element is not None and display_text:\n514\t                if styler is not None:\n515\t                    from .style import Element\n516\t\n517\t                    # Print with styling to stderr so it doesn't mix with\n518\t                    # any stdout output the caller may be collecting.\n519\t        