{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ej6HoAJEkJAg5v5ynDYBsh","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: \"PRD-230\"\n3\ttitle: \"Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\"\n4\tkind: task\n5\tstatus: done\n6\tpriority: medium\n7\teffort: xs\n8\tcapability: trivial\n9\tparent: null\n10\tdepends_on: []\n11\tblocks: []\n12\timpacts:\n13\t  - .git/hooks/pre-push\n14\t  - .github/settings.yml\n15\t  - scripts/install-hooks.sh\n16\t  - README.md\n17\tworkflow: null\n18\ttarget_version: null\n19\tcreated: 2026-04-08\n20\tupdated: '2026-04-08'\n21\ttags:\n22\t  - harness\n23\t  - hygiene\n24\t  - safety\n25\t---\n26\t\n27\t# Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\n28\t\n29\t## Summary\n30\t\n31\tPrevent direct pushes to `main`. Two layers of defense:\n32\t\n33\t1. **Local pre-push hook** at `.git/hooks/pre-push` that refuses any push whose target is `refs/heads/main`. Fast feedback — fails before the network round-trip — and works for any contributor (human or agent) running locally.\n34\t2. **GitHub branch protection rules** on `main` that require all changes to land via pull request and reject direct pushes server-side. Belt-and-suspenders for the case where the local hook is missing or bypassed with `--no-verify`.\n35\t\n36\tA small `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the pre-push hook into `.git/hooks/` since git won't track files in that directory. README documents the install step.\n37\t\n38\t## Motivation\n39\t\n40\t**Concrete incident (2026-04-08):** during a design refresh session, an AI assistant ended up checked out on `main` after merges synced and committed two PRD design files (`PRD-228`, `PRD-229`) directly to main, bypassing the usual PR review path. The content was harmless docs, but the process broke the project's \"everything goes through a PR\" norm.\n41\t\n42\tThat's exactly the failure mode this PRD prevents. The `main` branch should be a **destination only** — a target for merges, never a target for `git push`. Making that an enforced rule (not a convention) eliminates the failure mode whether the contributor is a human in a hurry, an AI assistant that lost track of its branch, or a misconfigured automation script.\n43\t\n44\t## Requirements\n45\t\n46\t1. A pre-push hook script at `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` (tracked) that:\n47\t   - Reads stdin (git's pre-push contract)\n48\t   - For each `<local_ref> <local_sha> <remote_ref> <remote_sha>` line, checks if `remote_ref == refs/heads/main`\n49\t   - If so, prints a clear error message and exits non-zero\n50\t   - Otherwise exits 0\n51\t2. An installer script `scripts/install-hooks.sh` that symlinks the tracked hooks into `.git/hooks/`. Idempotent — re-running is a no-op.\n52\t3. README documents: \"First time setup: run `./scripts/install-hooks.sh` after cloning.\"\n53\t4. A GitHub branch protection rule on `main`:\n54\t   - Require pull request before merging\n55\t   - Require at least 0 approvals (solo project for now; bump later)\n56\t   - Require status checks to pass (the existing CI from PRD-530 once that lands; until then no required checks)\n57\t   - Disallow force pushes\n58\t   - Disallow deletions\n59\t5. The protection rules are documented either in a `.github/settings.yml` file (managed by the [Settings App](https://github.com/apps/settings)) OR in README as a manual setup step. Recommendation: README + manual for now since adding the Settings App is its own bit of overhead.\n60\t6. Test: try to push directly to main from a clean checkout with hooks installed; expect failure with a clear message.\n61\t\n62\t## Technical Approach\n63\t\n64\t### `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push`\n65\t\n66\t```bash\n67\t#!/usr/bin/env bash\n68\t# Refuses any push targeting refs/heads/main on origin.\n69\t# Override with --no-verify if you really mean it (but you shouldn't).\n70\t\n71\tset -euo pipefail\n72\t\n73\tprotected_branch=\"refs/heads/main\"\n74\t\n75\twhile read -r local_ref local_sha remote_ref remote_sha; do\n76\t    if [ \"$remote_ref\" = \"$protected_branch\" ]; then\n77\t        echo \"\"\n78\t        echo \"ERROR: direct push to main is not allowed.\"\n79\t        echo \"\"\n80\t        echo \"  Local:  $local_ref ($local_sha)\"\n81\t        echo \"  Remote: $remote_ref\"\n82\t        echo \"\"\n83\t        echo \"Open a pull request instead:\"\n84\t        echo \"  1. Create a branch:  git checkout -b <type>/<short-description>\"\n85\t        echo \"  2. Push the branch:  git push -u origin <branch>\"\n86\t        echo \"  3. Open a PR:        gh pr create --base main\"\n87\t        echo \"\"\n88\t        echo \"If you absolutely must push to main, bypass with --no-verify.\"\n89\t        echo \"(But you should not. The point of this hook is to make you stop and think.)\"\n90\t        echo \"\"\n91\t        exit 1\n92\t    fi\n93\tdone\n94\t\n95\texit 0\n96\t```\n97\t\n98\t### `scripts/install-hooks.sh`\n99\t\n100\t```bash\n101\t#!/usr/bin/env bash\n102\tset -euo pipefail\n103\t\n104\tREPO_ROOT=\"$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)\"\n105\tHOOKS_SRC=\"$REPO_ROOT/.scripts/git-hooks\"\n106\tHOOKS_DST=\"$REPO_ROOT/.git/hooks\"\n107\t\n108\tif [ ! -d \"$HOOKS_SRC\" ]; then\n109\t    echo \"ERROR: $HOOKS_SRC not found\"\n110\t    exit 1\n111\tfi\n112\t\n113\tmkdir -p \"$HOOKS_DST\"\n114\t\n115\tfor hook in \"$HOOKS_SRC\"/*; do\n116\t    name=\"$(basename \"$hook\")\"\n117\t    target=\"$HOOKS_DST/$name\"\n118\t    if [ -L \"$target\" ] && [ \"$(readlink \"$target\")\" = \"$hook\" ]; then\n119\t        echo \"  $name already linked\"\n120\t        continue\n121\t    fi\n122\t    if [ -e \"$target\" ]; then\n123\t        echo \"  $name exists (not a symlink) — backing up to $name.bak\"\n124\t        mv \"$target\" \"$target.bak\"\n125\t    fi\n126\t    ln -s \"$hook\" \"$target\"\n127\t    chmod +x \"$hook\"\n128\t    echo \"  $name installed\"\n129\tdone\n130\t\n131\techo \"\"\n132\techo \"Hooks installed. Re-run any time after cloning.\"\n133\t```\n134\t\n135\t### GitHub branch protection (manual setup)\n136\t\n137\tIn repo Settings → Branches → Add rule for `main`:\n138\t\n139\t- ✓ Require a pull request before merging\n140\t- ✓ Require linear history (optional, prevents merge commits if you prefer squash-only)\n141\t- ✓ Do not allow force pushes\n142\t- ✓ Do not allow deletions\n143\t- ✗ Approvals required: 0 (solo project, bump when collaborators join)\n144\t\n145\tDocument this in README under \"Repo conventions\" so anyone setting up a fork knows.\n146\t\n147\t## Acceptance Criteria\n148\t\n149\t- [ ] AC-1: `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` exists, is executable, and refuses pushes to `refs/heads/main` with a clear message\n150\t- [ ] AC-2: `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the hook into `.git/hooks/`; idempotent on re-run\n151\t- [ ] AC-3: After running the installer, `git push origin HEAD:main` from a feature branch fails with the hook's error message\n152\t- [ ] AC-4: The hook does NOT block pushes to feature branches (e.g. `git push -u origin feature/foo` works)\n153\t- [ ] AC-5: README documents the install step in the contributor setup section\n154\t- [ ] AC-6: GitHub branch protection rule is enabled on `main` (manually verified — no API automation in this PRD)\n155\t- [ ] AC-7: A test push directly to main from a fresh checkout (with hooks installed) fails locally before reaching the network\n156\t\n157\t## Open Questions\n158\t\n159\t- [ ] Should the hook also protect against pushes to `release/*` or other long-lived branches? Recommendation: not yet — only main exists today; revisit when there are multiple protected branches\n160\t- [ ] Should the installer be invoked automatically by `mise install` or `uv sync`? Tempting but invasive — recommendation: keep it explicit and documented. A user who's just inspecting the repo shouldn't have hooks silently installed\n161\t- [ ] Is `.scripts/git-hooks/` the right location vs `scripts/git-hooks/`? The dot-prefix is consistent with `.darkfactory/` (PRD-222) for \"tooling state, not user code\". Recommendation: `.scripts/git-hooks/`\n162\t- [ ] Should the hook print the user's current branch in its error message (\"you're on `xyz`, push that instead\")? Yes, small UX improvement — add to the script\n163\t\n164\t## Relationship to other PRDs\n165\t\n166\t- **PR #18 / PR #19** — the merges that triggered the incident this PRD prevents\n167\t- **PRD-217** (process lock) — same defense-in-depth pattern (local enforcement + clear error message)\n168\t- **PRD-530** (CI setup) — the GitHub branch protection rule will eventually require the CI status check to pass; until then it just requires \"PR exists\"\n169\t- **PRD-224** (harness invariants) — broader theme of \"make wrong actions impossible, not discouraged\"\n170\t\n171\t## Why this is small\n172\t\n173\tThis is a **30-minute task**. Two short shell scripts, an installer, a README paragraph, a manual GitHub setting. No new Python code, no test infrastructure, no design decisions. The main reason it gets its own PRD instead of being a drive-by commit is that the README change + the manual GH setup are the kind of thing that's easy to forget — having a PRD makes the work visible and tracked.\n174\t\n[result-id: r3]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01DMaYaC743Bch6jjuWoX88e","session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"370bd57c-be35-48b2-b319-3612a5c88de9","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:32:20.982Z"}
