{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RLtD4GizMtLMDvnXvXu61b","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Summary\n\nI found the relevant timeout configuration in the DarkFactory codebase. Here are the key findings:\n\n### Primary Location: Timeout Default Value\n**File:** `/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts/src/darkfactory/invoke.py`\n- **Line 339:** Function signature for `invoke_claude()` has parameter `timeout_seconds: int = 600`\n- **Line 444:** Timeout is applied: `deadline = time.monotonic() + timeout_seconds`\n- **Line 552:** Timeout failure message uses the timeout value\n\n### Where Timeout is Set for Agent Invocations\n**File:** `/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts/src/darkfactory/runner.py`\n- **Lines 293-302:** The `_run_agent()` function calls `invoke_claude()` but **does NOT pass a `timeout_seconds` parameter**, meaning it always uses the default of 600 seconds (10 minutes)\n\n### Key Details:\n1. **Default timeout:** 600 seconds (10 minutes), not 600000 milliseconds\n2. **No timeout configuration module found:** There is no `darkfactory/timeouts.py` or separate config module for timeouts\n3. **Timeout mechanism:** Uses a watchdog thread that monitors elapsed time and kills the process if it exceeds the deadline\n4. **Timeout error handling:** When timed out, returns `InvokeResult` with `success=False` and `failure_reason=f\"timeout after {timeout_seconds}s\"`\n\nIf you need to add effort-based (adaptive) timeouts based on capability levels, the change would need to be made in the `_run_agent()` function in `runner.py` to calculate and pass `timeout_seconds` to `invoke_claude()`."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"193bf3e5-7dfe-4ae6-988b-56eb1491dd1e","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:32:42.587Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"In /Users