{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DMaYaC743Bch6jjuWoX88e","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The template file doesn't exist in the accessible directories. Here's your complete reference PRD with `kind: task` format:\n\n## PRD Example: PRD-230-main-branch-protection.md\n\n```markdown\n---\nid: \"PRD-230\"\ntitle: \"Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\"\nkind: task\nstatus: done\npriority: medium\neffort: xs\ncapability: trivial\nparent: null\ndepends_on: []\nblocks: []\nimpacts:\n  - .git/hooks/pre-push\n  - .github/settings.yml\n  - scripts/install-hooks.sh\n  - README.md\nworkflow: null\ntarget_version: null\ncreated: 2026-04-08\nupdated: '2026-04-08'\ntags:\n  - harness\n  - hygiene\n  - safety\n---\n\n# Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\n\n## Summary\n\nPrevent direct pushes to `main`. Two layers of defense:\n\n1. **Local pre-push hook** at `.git/hooks/pre-push` that refuses any push whose target is `refs/heads/main`. Fast feedback — fails before the network round-trip — and works for any contributor (human or agent) running locally.\n2. **GitHub branch protection rules** on `main` that require all changes to land via pull request and reject direct pushes server-side. Belt-and-suspenders for the case where the local hook is missing or bypassed with `--no-verify`.\n\nA small `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the pre-push hook into `.git/hooks/` since git won't track files in that directory. README documents the install step.\n\n## Motivation\n\n**Concrete incident (2026-04-08):** during a design refresh session, an AI assistant ended up checked out on `main` after merges synced and committed two PRD design files (`PRD-228`, `PRD-229`) directly to main, bypassing the usual PR review path. The content was harmless docs, but the process broke the project's \"everything goes through a PR\" norm.\n\nThat's exactly the failure mode this PRD prevents. The `main` branch should be a **destination only** — a target for merges, never a target for `git push`. Making that an enforced rule (not a convention) eliminates the failure mode whether the contributor is a human in a hurry, an AI assistant that lost track of its branch, or a misconfigured automation script.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. A pre-push hook script at `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` (tracked) that:\n   - Reads stdin (git's pre-push contract)\n   - For each `<local_ref> <local_sha> <remote_ref> <remote_sha>` line, checks if `remote_ref == refs/heads/main`\n   - If so, prints a clear error message and exits non-zero\n   - Otherwise exits 0\n2. An installer script `scripts/install-hooks.sh` that symlinks the tracked hooks into `.git/hooks/`. Idempotent — re-running is a no-op.\n3. README documents: \"First time setup: run `./scripts/install-hooks.sh` after cloning.\"\n4. A GitHub branch protection rule on `main`:\n   - Require pull request before merging\n   - Require at least 0 approvals (solo project for now; bump later)\n   - Require status checks to pass (the existing CI from PRD-530 once that lands; until then no required checks)\n   - Disallow force pushes\n   - Disallow deletions\n5. The protection rules are documented either in a `.github/settings.yml` file (managed by the [Settings App](https://github.com/apps/settings)) OR in README as a manual setup step. Recommendation: README + manual for now since adding the Settings App is its own bit of overhead.\n6. Test: try to push directly to main from a clean checkout with hooks installed; expect failure with a clear message.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push`\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Refuses any push targeting refs/heads/main on origin.\n# Override with --no-verify if you really mean it (but you shouldn't).\n\nset -euo pipefail\n\nprotected_branch=\"refs/heads/main\"\n\nwhile read -r local_ref local_sha remote_ref remote_sha; do\n    if [ \"$remote_ref\" = \"$protected_branch\" ]; then\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"ERROR: direct push to main is not allowed.\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"  Local:  $local_ref ($local_sha)\"\n        echo \"  Remote: $remote_ref\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"Open a pull request instead:\"\n        echo \"  1. Create a branch:  git checkout -b <type>/<short-description>\"\n        echo \"  2. Push the branch:  git push -u origin <branch>\"\n        echo \"  3. Open a PR:        gh pr create --base main\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"If you absolutely must push to main, bypass with --no-verify.\"\n        echo \"(But you should not. The point of this hook is to make you stop and think.)\"\n        echo \"\"\n        exit 1\n    fi\ndone\n\nexit 0\n```\n\n### `scripts/install-hooks.sh`\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nREPO_ROOT=\"$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)\"\nHOOKS_SRC=\"$REPO_ROOT/.scripts/git-hooks\"\nHOOKS_DST=\"$REPO_ROOT/.git/hooks\"\n\nif [ ! -d \"$HOOKS_SRC\" ]; then\n    echo \"ERROR: $HOOKS_SRC not found\"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\nmkdir -p \"$HOOKS_DST\"\n\nfor hook in \"$HOOKS_SRC\"/*; do\n    name=\"$(basename \"$hook\")\"\n    target=\"$HOOKS_DST/$name\"\n    if [ -L \"$target\" ] && [ \"$(readlink \"$target\")\" = \"$hook\" ]; then\n        echo \"  $name already linked\"\n        continue\n    fi\n    if [ -e \"$target\" ]; then\n        echo \"  $name exists (not a symlink) — backing up to $name.bak\"\n        mv \"$target\" \"$target.bak\"\n    fi\n    ln -s \"$hook\" \"$target\"\n    chmod +x \"$hook\"\n    echo \"  $name installed\"\ndone\n\necho \"\"\necho \"Hooks installed. Re-run any time after cloning.\"\n```\n\n### GitHub branch protection (manual setup)\n\nIn repo Settings → Branches → Add rule for `main`:\n\n- ✓ Require a pull request before merging\n- ✓ Require linear history (optional, prevents merge commits if you prefer squash-only)\n- ✓ Do not allow force pushes\n- ✓ Do not allow deletions\n- ✗ Approvals required: 0 (solo project, bump when collaborators join)\n\nDocument this in README under \"Repo conventions\" so anyone setting up a fork knows.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` exists, is executable, and refuses pushes to `refs/heads/main` with a clear message\n- [ ] AC-2: `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the hook into `.git/hooks/`; idempotent on re-run\n- [ ] AC-3: After running the installer, `git push origin HEAD:main` from a feature branch fails with the hook's error message\n- [ ] AC-4: The hook does NOT block pushes to feature branches (e.g. `git push -u origin feature/foo` works)\n- [ ] AC-5: README documents the install step in the contributor setup section\n- [ ] AC-6: GitHub branch protection rule is enabled on `main` (manually verified — no API automation in this PRD)\n- [ ] AC-7: A test push directly to main from a fresh checkout (with hooks installed) fails locally before reaching the network\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- [ ] Should the hook also protect against pushes to `release/*` or other long-lived branches? Recommendation: not yet — only main exists today; revisit when there are multiple protected branches\n- [ ] Should the installer be invoked automatically by `mise install` or `uv sync`? Tempting but invasive — recommendation: keep it explicit and documented. A user who's just inspecting the repo shouldn't have hooks silently installed\n- [ ] Is `.scripts/git-hooks/` the right location vs `scripts/git-hooks/`? The dot-prefix is consistent with `.darkfactory/` (PRD-222) for \"tooling state, not user code\". Recommendation: `.scripts/git-hooks/`\n- [ ] Should the hook print the user's current branch in its error message (\"you're on `xyz`, push that instead\")? Yes, small UX improvement — add to the script\n\n## Relationship to other PRDs\n\n- **PR #18 / PR #19** — the merges that triggered the incident this PRD prevents\n- **PRD-217** (process lock) — same defense-in-depth pattern (local enforcement + clear error message)\n- **PRD-530** (CI setup) — the GitHub branch protection rule will eventually require the CI status check to pass; until then it just requires \"PR exists\"\n- **PRD-224** (harness invariants) — broader theme of \"make wrong actions impossible, not discouraged\"\n\n## Why this is small\n\nThis is a **30-minute task**. Two short shell scripts, an installer, a README paragraph, a manual GitHub setting. No new Python code, no test infrastructure, no design decisions. The main reason it gets its own PRD instead of being a drive-by commit is that the README change + the manual GH setup are the kind of thing that's easy to forget — having a PRD makes the work visible and tracked.\n```\n\n## Summary\n\n**Template file status:** `/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/prds/_template.md` does not exist in the accessible directories.\n\n**Frontmatter structure for `kind: task` PRDs** includes these fields:\n- `id`: PRD identifier\n- `title`: Human-readable title\n- `kind`: Set to `task`\n- `status`: done/active/backlog/etc.\n- `priority`: high/medium/low\n- `effort`: xs/s/m/l/xl (sizing)\n- `capability`: trivial/simple/moderate/complex\n- `parent`: null or parent PRD ID\n- `depends_on`: list of blocking PRDs\n- `blocks`: list of PRDs this blocks\n- `impacts`: list of files affected\n- `workflow`: null or workflow reference\n- `target_version`: null or version string\n- `created`: date created\n- `updated`: date last updated\n- `tags`: list of tags\n\nThe example above (PRD-230) is a complete, properly formatted task PRD with Summary, Motivation, Requirements, Technical Approach, Acceptance Criteria, Open Questions, and Relationship sections."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"47af8562-b22b-4ae5-afa0-1886472f4954","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:32:45.379Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"In /Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/prds/, find an existing PRD file with `kind: task` in its frontmatter. Read it fully and return its complete contents so I can use it as a format reference. Also check if prds/_template.md exists. Quick search.","agentId":"ae882908663cc3aad","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The template file doesn't exist in the accessible directories. Here's your complete reference PRD with `kind: task` format:\n\n## PRD Example: PRD-230-main-branch-protection.md\n\n```markdown\n---\nid: \"PRD-230\"\ntitle: \"Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\"\nkind: task\nstatus: done\npriority: medium\neffort: xs\ncapability: trivial\nparent: null\ndepends_on: []\nblocks: []\nimpacts:\n  - .git/hooks/pre-push\n  - .github/settings.yml\n  - scripts/install-hooks.sh\n  - README.md\nworkflow: null\ntarget_version: null\ncreated: 2026-04-08\nupdated: '2026-04-08'\ntags:\n  - harness\n  - hygiene\n  - safety\n---\n\n# Main branch protection: refuse direct pushes locally and on GitHub\n\n## Summary\n\nPrevent direct pushes to `main`. Two layers of defense:\n\n1. **Local pre-push hook** at `.git/hooks/pre-push` that refuses any push whose target is `refs/heads/main`. Fast feedback — fails before the network round-trip — and works for any contributor (human or agent) running locally.\n2. **GitHub branch protection rules** on `main` that require all changes to land via pull request and reject direct pushes server-side. Belt-and-suspenders for the case where the local hook is missing or bypassed with `--no-verify`.\n\nA small `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the pre-push hook into `.git/hooks/` since git won't track files in that directory. README documents the install step.\n\n## Motivation\n\n**Concrete incident (2026-04-08):** during a design refresh session, an AI assistant ended up checked out on `main` after merges synced and committed two PRD design files (`PRD-228`, `PRD-229`) directly to main, bypassing the usual PR review path. The content was harmless docs, but the process broke the project's \"everything goes through a PR\" norm.\n\nThat's exactly the failure mode this PRD prevents. The `main` branch should be a **destination only** — a target for merges, never a target for `git push`. Making that an enforced rule (not a convention) eliminates the failure mode whether the contributor is a human in a hurry, an AI assistant that lost track of its branch, or a misconfigured automation script.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. A pre-push hook script at `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` (tracked) that:\n   - Reads stdin (git's pre-push contract)\n   - For each `<local_ref> <local_sha> <remote_ref> <remote_sha>` line, checks if `remote_ref == refs/heads/main`\n   - If so, prints a clear error message and exits non-zero\n   - Otherwise exits 0\n2. An installer script `scripts/install-hooks.sh` that symlinks the tracked hooks into `.git/hooks/`. Idempotent — re-running is a no-op.\n3. README documents: \"First time setup: run `./scripts/install-hooks.sh` after cloning.\"\n4. A GitHub branch protection rule on `main`:\n   - Require pull request before merging\n   - Require at least 0 approvals (solo project for now; bump later)\n   - Require status checks to pass (the existing CI from PRD-530 once that lands; until then no required checks)\n   - Disallow force pushes\n   - Disallow deletions\n5. The protection rules are documented either in a `.github/settings.yml` file (managed by the [Settings App](https://github.com/apps/settings)) OR in README as a manual setup step. Recommendation: README + manual for now since adding the Settings App is its own bit of overhead.\n6. Test: try to push directly to main from a clean checkout with hooks installed; expect failure with a clear message.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push`\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Refuses any push targeting refs/heads/main on origin.\n# Override with --no-verify if you really mean it (but you shouldn't).\n\nset -euo pipefail\n\nprotected_branch=\"refs/heads/main\"\n\nwhile read -r local_ref local_sha remote_ref remote_sha; do\n    if [ \"$remote_ref\" = \"$protected_branch\" ]; then\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"ERROR: direct push to main is not allowed.\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"  Local:  $local_ref ($local_sha)\"\n        echo \"  Remote: $remote_ref\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"Open a pull request instead:\"\n        echo \"  1. Create a branch:  git checkout -b <type>/<short-description>\"\n        echo \"  2. Push the branch:  git push -u origin <branch>\"\n        echo \"  3. Open a PR:        gh pr create --base main\"\n        echo \"\"\n        echo \"If you absolutely must push to main, bypass with --no-verify.\"\n        echo \"(But you should not. The point of this hook is to make you stop and think.)\"\n        echo \"\"\n        exit 1\n    fi\ndone\n\nexit 0\n```\n\n### `scripts/install-hooks.sh`\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nREPO_ROOT=\"$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)\"\nHOOKS_SRC=\"$REPO_ROOT/.scripts/git-hooks\"\nHOOKS_DST=\"$REPO_ROOT/.git/hooks\"\n\nif [ ! -d \"$HOOKS_SRC\" ]; then\n    echo \"ERROR: $HOOKS_SRC not found\"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\nmkdir -p \"$HOOKS_DST\"\n\nfor hook in \"$HOOKS_SRC\"/*; do\n    name=\"$(basename \"$hook\")\"\n    target=\"$HOOKS_DST/$name\"\n    if [ -L \"$target\" ] && [ \"$(readlink \"$target\")\" = \"$hook\" ]; then\n        echo \"  $name already linked\"\n        continue\n    fi\n    if [ -e \"$target\" ]; then\n        echo \"  $name exists (not a symlink) — backing up to $name.bak\"\n        mv \"$target\" \"$target.bak\"\n    fi\n    ln -s \"$hook\" \"$target\"\n    chmod +x \"$hook\"\n    echo \"  $name installed\"\ndone\n\necho \"\"\necho \"Hooks installed. Re-run any time after cloning.\"\n```\n\n### GitHub branch protection (manual setup)\n\nIn repo Settings → Branches → Add rule for `main`:\n\n- ✓ Require a pull request before merging\n- ✓ Require linear history (optional, prevents merge commits if you prefer squash-only)\n- ✓ Do not allow force pushes\n- ✓ Do not allow deletions\n- ✗ Approvals required: 0 (solo project, bump when collaborators join)\n\nDocument this in README under \"Repo conventions\" so anyone setting up a fork knows.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: `.scripts/git-hooks/pre-push` exists, is executable, and refuses pushes to `refs/heads/main` with a clear message\n- [ ] AC-2: `scripts/install-hooks.sh` symlinks the hook into `.git/hooks/`; idempotent on re-run\n- [ ] AC-3: After running the installer, `git push origin HEAD:main` from a feature branch fails with the hook's error message\n- [ ] AC-4: The hook does NOT block pushes to feature branches (e.g. `git push -u origin feature/foo` works)\n- [ ] AC-5: README documents the install step in the contributor setup section\n- [ ] AC-6: GitHub branch protection rule is enabled on `main` (manually verified — no API automation in this PRD)\n- [ ] AC-7: A test push directly to main from a fresh checkout (with hooks installed) fails locally before reaching the network\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- [ ] Should the hook also protect against pushes to `release/*` or other long-lived branches? Recommendation: not yet — only main exists today; revisit when there are multiple protected branches\n- [ ] Should the installer be invoked automatically by `mise install` or `uv sync`? Tempting but invasive — recommendation: keep it explicit and documented. A user who's just inspecting the repo shouldn't have hooks silently installed\n- [ ] Is `.scripts/git-hooks/` the right location vs `scripts/git-hooks/`? The dot-prefix is consistent with `.darkfactory/` (PRD-222) for \"tooling state, not user code\". Recommendation: `.scripts/git-hooks/`\n- [ ] Should the hook print the user's current branch in its error message (\"you're on `xyz`, push that instead\")? Yes, small UX improvement — add to the script\n\n## Relationship to other PRDs\n\n- **PR #18 / PR #19** — the merges that triggered the incident this PRD prevents\n- **PRD-217** (process lock) — same defense-in-depth pattern (local enforcement + clear error message)\n- **PRD-530** (CI setup) — the GitHub branch protection rule will eventually require the CI status check to pass; until then it just requires \"PR exists\"\n- **PRD-224** (harness invariants) — broader theme of \"make wrong actions impossible, not discouraged\"\n\n## Why this is small\n\nThis is a **30-minute task**. Two short shell scripts, an installer, a README paragraph, a manual GitHub setting. No new Python code, no test infrastructure, no design decisions. The main reason it gets its own PRD instead of being a drive-by commit is that the README change + the manual GH setup are the kind of thing that's easy to forget — having a PRD makes the work visible and tracked.\n```\n\n## Summary\n\n**Template file status:** `/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/prds/_template.md` does not exist in the accessible directories.\n\n**Frontmatter structure for `kind: task` PRDs** includes these fields:\n- `id`: PRD identifier\n- `title`: Human-readable title\n- `kind`: Set to `task`\n- `status`: done/active/backlog/etc.\n- `priority`: high/medium/low\n- `effort`: xs/s/m/l/xl (sizing)\n- `capability`: trivial/simple/moderate/complex\n- `parent`: null or parent PRD ID\n- `depends_on`: list of blocking PRDs\n- `blocks`: list of PRDs this blocks\n- `impacts`: list of files affected\n- `workflow`: null or workflow reference\n- `target_version`: null or version string\n- `created`: date created\n- `updated`: date last updated\n- `tags`: list of tags\n\nThe example above (PRD-230) is a complete, properly formatted task PRD with Summary, Motivation, Requirements, Technical Approach, Acceptance Criteria, Open Questions, and Relationship sections."}],"totalDurationMs":35530,"totalTokens":26040,"totalToolUseCount":5,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":116,"cache_read_input_tokens":23312,"output_tokens":2607,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":116},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":1,"searchCount":2,"bashCount":2,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01G58idpVahkqgvouAwLMFjF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the PRD and the codebase. Let me plan the decomposition.\n\nKey areas from the PRD:\n1. Timeout resolution logic (pure function) - `resolve_timeout(prd, config, cli_override) -> int`\n2. Config table in `.darkfactory/config.toml` for timeout mapping\n3. PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes:` field support\n4. CLI `--timeout` flag on `prd run`\n5. Integration into runner.py (replace hardcoded 600)\n6. Logging the resolved timeout and source\n\n\n7. Graceful timeout handling (check for terminal result event before marking as failed)\n8. Unit tests\n\nI'm breaking this down into five focused tasks: first, I'll create the core timeout resolution module with the pure function and default mappings, then add config table support, extend the PRD schema with the timeout field, implement the CLI flag, and finally integrate everything into the runner while adding comprehensive tests.\n\nActually, reconsidering the scope—the effort is marked as small, so I should consolidate this. The core module with tests handles the pure logic, config support covers the timeout table, and a single integration task can handle the frontmatter field, CLI flag, runner integration, logging, and graceful timeout handling all together. I'm realizing tasks 1 and 2 are too tightly coupled—the resolution function fundamentally needs to handle all override sources together, so splitting them feels artificial. Let me consolidate into a cleaner structure where the core timeout resolution module handles defaults, effort mapping, capability multipliers, and all config/frontmatter/CLI sources in one place, then wire that into the runner with logging, and finally add graceful timeout handling for late result events. I need to figure out where the `prd run` command is defined so I can add the `--timeout` CLI flag in the right place, then finalize these three tasks.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":477,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2982,"cache_read_input_tokens":21754,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2982},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"d7588169-10a4-467f-b5f8-80491aad3c9a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01G58idpVahkqgvouAwLMFjF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have full context. Let me plan and write the child PRDs.\n\n**Decomposition plan (3 tasks):**\n\n1. **PRD-542.1** — Core timeout resolution module (pure function + unit tests)\n2. **PRD-542.2** — Integration into runner + CLI flag + logging (depends on .1)\n3. **PRD-542.3** — Graceful timeout handling for late result events (depends on .2)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":477,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2982,"cache_read_input_tokens":21754,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2982},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"03c61891-32ff-4911-9ac2-7f4d1444723a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01G58idpVahkqgvouAwLMFjF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014vXziQiQ7ZPTTqt6TCMJuS","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts/prds/PRD-542.1-timeout-resolution-module.md","content":"---\nid: \"PRD-542.1\"\ntitle: \"Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\"\nkind: task\nstatus: ready\npriority: medium\neffort: s\ncapability: simple\nparent: \"[[PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts]]\"\ndepends_on: []\nblocks:\n  - \"[[PRD-542.2-integrate-timeout-into-runner]]\"\nimpacts:\n  - src/darkfactory/timeouts.py\n  - .darkfactory/config.toml\n  - tests/test_timeouts.py\nworkflow: null\ntarget_version: null\ncreated: 2026-04-08\nupdated: 2026-04-08\ntags:\n  - harness\n---\n\n# Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\n\n## Summary\n\nCreate a new `darkfactory/timeouts.py` module exposing a pure function `resolve_timeout(prd, config, cli_override) -> int` that computes the agent task timeout in seconds. The function implements a clear resolution order: CLI flag > PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` > config table lookup by effort × capability multiplier > built-in defaults. This task also adds the config schema for the timeout table in `.darkfactory/config.toml` and comprehensive unit tests.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. Create `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py` with a `resolve_timeout()` function.\n2. Built-in default effort → timeout mapping:\n   - `xs` → 300s (5 min)\n   - `s` → 600s (10 min)\n   - `m` → 1200s (20 min)\n   - `l` → 2400s (40 min)\n   - `xl` → 4500s (75 min)\n3. Capability multiplier applied on top of effort base: `simple` ×1.0, `moderate` ×1.25, `complex` ×1.5. When `capability` is `trivial` or missing, use ×1.0.\n4. Resolution order (highest priority wins):\n   - `cli_override` (integer minutes, if provided)\n   - PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` field (integer minutes)\n   - Config table lookup (`[timeouts]` section in `.darkfactory/config.toml`) by effort × capability multiplier\n   - Built-in defaults × capability multiplier\n5. The function returns an integer (seconds) and a string describing the source (e.g. `\"cli\"`, `\"prd_frontmatter\"`, `\"config\"`, `\"default\"`).\n6. Add a `[timeouts]` section to `.darkfactory/config.toml` schema with keys for each effort tier (values in minutes) and capability multipliers.\n7. If the PRD has no `effort` field, fall back to `s` (10 min) as the default.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py`\n\n```python\nDEFAULT_EFFORT_TIMEOUTS = {\n    \"xs\": 300,\n    \"s\": 600,\n    \"m\": 1200,\n    \"l\": 2400,\n    \"xl\": 4500,\n}\n\nCAPABILITY_MULTIPLIERS = {\n    \"trivial\": 1.0,\n    \"simple\": 1.0,\n    \"moderate\": 1.25,\n    \"complex\": 1.5,\n}\n\ndef resolve_timeout(\n    effort: str | None,\n    capability: str | None,\n    timeout_minutes_frontmatter: int | None,\n    config_timeouts: dict | None,\n    cli_override: int | None,\n) -> tuple[int, str]:\n    \"\"\"Return (timeout_seconds, source_description).\"\"\"\n    ...\n```\n\n### Config schema addition (`.darkfactory/config.toml`)\n\n```toml\n[timeouts]\nxs = 5       # minutes\ns = 10\nm = 20\nl = 40\nxl = 75\n\n[timeouts.capability_multipliers]\ntrivial = 1.0\nsimple = 1.0\nmoderate = 1.25\ncomplex = 1.5\n```\n\n### Unit tests (`tests/test_timeouts.py`)\n\nTable-driven tests covering:\n- Every effort tier with default mapping\n- Every capability multiplier\n- PRD frontmatter override takes precedence over config/defaults\n- CLI override takes precedence over everything\n- Config table overrides built-in defaults\n- Missing effort falls back to `s`\n- Missing capability uses multiplier 1.0\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: `resolve_timeout()` returns correct seconds for each effort tier using built-in defaults.\n- [ ] AC-2: Capability multiplier is applied correctly on top of effort base.\n- [ ] AC-3: PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` overrides computed value.\n- [ ] AC-4: CLI override (minutes) overrides everything.\n- [ ] AC-5: Config table values override built-in defaults.\n- [ ] AC-6: Function returns both timeout value and source string.\n- [ ] AC-7: Unit tests cover all resolution paths with table-driven tests.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":477,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2982,"cache_read_input_tokens":21754,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2982},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"8163f410-813e-4866-8945-56c5026bd6b7"}
