is threaded through to `resolve_timeout()` as the CLI override.\n4. When a task starts, log a message like: `Timeout: 1200s (source: default, effort=m, capability×1.0)` so failures are diagnosable.\n5. Read timeout config from `.darkfactory/config.toml` `[timeouts]` section if present.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `src/darkfactory/runner.py`\n\nIn the `_run_agent()` method (around line 293-302), before calling `invoke_claude()`:\n\n```python\nfrom darkfactory.timeouts import resolve_timeout\n\ntimeout_seconds, timeout_source = resolve_timeout(\n    effort=prd.frontmatter.get(\"effort\"),\n    capability=prd.frontmatter.get(\"capability\"),\n    timeout_minutes_frontmatter=prd.frontmatter.get(\"timeout_minutes\"),\n    config_timeouts=self.config.get(\"timeouts\"),\n    cli_override=self.cli_timeout_minutes,\n)\nlogger.info(\"Timeout: %ds (source: %s)\", timeout_seconds, timeout_source)\n```\n\nThen pass `timeout_seconds=timeout_seconds` to `invoke_claude()`.\n\n### `src/darkfactory/cli.py`\n\nAdd `--timeout` option to the `prd run` command:\n\n```python\n@click.option(\"--timeout\", type=int, default=None, help=\"Override timeout in minutes\")\n```\n\nThread the value through to the runner.\n\n### Config reading\n\nIf `.darkfactory/config.toml` has a `[timeouts]` section, parse it and pass to `resolve_timeout()`. If the section doesn't exist, pass `None` (built-in defaults apply).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: Agent tasks use effort-based timeouts from `resolve_timeout()` instead of hardcoded 600s.\n- [ ] AC-2: `prd run --timeout 30` sets a 30-minute timeout that overrides all other sources.\n- [ ] AC-3: When a task starts, the log shows the resolved timeout value and source.\n- [ ] AC-4: Config timeouts from `.darkfactory/config.toml` are read and passed to `resolve_timeout()`.\n- [ ] AC-5: When no config or CLI override is present, the default effort-based mapping is used.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01G58idpVahkqgvouAwLMFjF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KgTda7EyCkrL1B9RnX8hz1","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts/prds/PRD-542.3-graceful-timeout-handling.md","content":"---\nid: \"PRD-542.3\"\ntitle: \"Graceful timeout handling for late result events\"\nkind: task\nstatus: ready\npriority: medium\neffort: xs\ncapability: simple\nparent: \"[[PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts]]\"\ndepends_on:\n  - \"[[PRD-542.2-integrate-timeout-into-runner]]\"\nblocks: []\nimpacts:\n  - src/darkfactory/invoke.py\n  - tests/test_invoke.py\nworkflow: null\ntarget_version: null\ncreated: 2026-04-08\nupdated: 2026-04-08\ntags:\n  - harness\n---\n\n# Graceful timeout handling for late result events\n\n## Summary\n\nWhen the timeout fires on an agent task, the harness currently marks the run as failed unconditionally. However, the agent process may have already emitted a terminal `result` event (as happened with PRD-541, which completed in ~770s but was killed at 600s). This task modifies the timeout handler in `invoke.py` to check for a terminal result event before declaring a timeout failure, preserving completed work that arrived just before the deadline.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. In the timeout handler in `invoke.py`, before marking the run as failed, scan the captured stdout for a terminal `{\"type\":\"result\", ...}` JSON line.\n2. If a terminal result event is found:\n   - Use its `is_error` / `subtype` fields to determine success or failure, instead of the timeout verdict.\n   - Log a warning: `\"Task timed out at {timeout}s but a terminal result event was found — using result verdict instead.\"`\n3. If no terminal result event is found, behave as today: mark the run as a timeout failure.\n4. Unit tests covering both cases: timeout with result event present, and timeout with no result event.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `src/darkfactory/invoke.py`\n\nIn the timeout handling path (around line 552 where the timeout failure is constructed), add a check:\n\n```python\nimport json\n\ndef _find_terminal_result(output_lines: list[str]) -> dict | None:\n    \"\"\"Scan output lines for the last {\"type\": \"result\", ...} JSON object.\"\"\"\n    for line in reversed(output_lines):\n        line = line.strip()\n        if not line.startswith(\"{\"):\n            continue\n        try:\n            obj = json.loads(line)\n            if obj.get(\"type\") == \"result\":\n                return obj\n        except json.JSONDecodeError:\n            continue\n    return None\n```\n\nIn the timeout branch:\n\n```python\nterminal_result = _find_terminal_result(captured_lines)\nif terminal_result is not None:\n    logger.warning(\n        \"Task timed out at %ds but terminal result event found — using result verdict\",\n        timeout_seconds,\n    )\n    # Build InvokeResult from terminal_result instead of timeout failure\n    ...\nelse:\n    # Existing timeout failure path\n    ...\n```\n\n### Tests (`tests/test_invoke.py`)\n\n- Test `_find_terminal_result` with: no result line, result line present, multiple JSON lines (picks the result one), malformed JSON lines.\n- Integration-style test: simulate a timeout where captured output contains a result event; verify the run is reported based on the result event, not as a timeout.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: When a task times out but has emitted a terminal `result` event, the run outcome is based on that event (not a timeout failure).\n- [ ] AC-2: When a task times out with no terminal result event, the run is reported as a timeout failure (existing behavior preserved).\n- [ ] AC-3: A warning is logged when a terminal result event is found after timeout.\n- [ ] AC-4: Unit tests cover both paths (result present, result absent) and edge cases (malformed JSON, multiple JSON lines).\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":477,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2982,"cache_read_input_tokens":21754,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2982},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b720c5ee-3335-470d-b4c3-b85e3ba705c0","uuid":"66ddfd5c-7efd-4f42-a48f-480ccdef3570"}
